t with curiosity which was the most fascinating way he had ever delved into things. His hands were restless. With each new idea there seemed to be a physical motion that needs were made.  The rigor of scholarly debate and the intellectual pursuit opened up a world he had only dreamed of. He remembers his first lecture, the professor's voice echoing in the grand halls; and his rapt eyes absorbing every word, feeling a surge of purpose and belonging. He could hear the knives that had cut the fishermen's fingertips 15 miles away without even meaning to.", '[observation] When James Moffat was 28, he spent the morning in studied silence after delivering a well-received lecture on theology. Very young scholars had sat around the room in a way that suggested collegiality for the first time, rather than their usual uncharacteristically cynical posturing.  The thrill of intellectual discourse and the respect of his peers filled him with a sense of accomplishment and joy. His mentor, Father McNeill, approached him afterward and more than usual hung his head as though he feared for James Moffat. "You have a gift, James," he said,  and James felt his chest swell with pride. "But remember, knowledge comes with great responsibility. Use it to guide and heal, not to divide."', "[observation]  Later again, when James Moffat was 36 the air was bitter and a chill had settled on the church and he was not much older than the young Elizabeth Lindsay she had come to him with doubts. It was haunted by fear of the religious tensions that were growing like a menance in the country of 1546. She needed a word to feel adequate in her own skin amongst the tensions. He recalled watching his father fishing in stormy seas, steady and determined. He channeled that spirit into his responses, seeking to bridge gaps and promote understanding. His efforts were met with resistance from some, but he remained steadfast in his mission, refusing to let fear dictate his actions. Her eyes betrayed Elizabeth's fear but she did not speak it and James felt a shudder of anticipation as he contemplated the challenges that lay ahead.", '[observation] "//Morning, October 1546// James Moffat finds himself standing on the cobblestone streets of St Andrews, the crisp autumn air nipping at his nose. The ruins of St Andrews Cathedral loom ominously in the distance, a stark reminder of the recent religious tumult. The bells of St Salvator\'s College chime in the background, signaling the start of a new academic day. The market is bustling with activity, vendors hawking their wares and students milling about, rushing to their lectures. Nearby, a group of scholars is engaged in a lively debate, their voices animated and passionate. James spots a familiar face—a fellow university mate hurrying toward him, looking a bit flustered."']}}, 'default rules --- Event: In the bright morning light illuminating the ruins of St Andrews Cathedral, James Moffat strolled through the narrow, cobblestone streets. The scholar from St Mary\'s College pondered deep philosophical thoughts when he noticed Elizabeth Lindsay approaching him. Elizabeth, his university mate from St Salvator\'s College, carried a troubled expression.\n\nUpon seeing Elizabeth, James, who was known for his resiliency and empathy, offered a warm, inviting smile and greeted her, “Good morning, Elizabeth.”\n\nJames immediately sensed Elizabeth\'s distress. He moved closer and asked, "Elizabeth, is everything alright? You seem troubled."\n\nElizabeth looked at James, her eyes filled with a mix of thoughts and worries. “James, I was coming to find you. There\'s been a disturbance at St Salvator\'s College.”\n\nJames\' curiosity and concern were piqued. He gestured toward a nearby bench beside the cathedral ruins and suggested, “Let\'s sit down. Tell me what happened.”\n\nHe listened attentively as Elizabeth explained, “There\'s been word a heated debate among our scholars. Tempers are getting out of hand, and I worry that if left unchecked, it might lead to a more significant issue.”\n\nSensing the gravity of the situation, James stood and said, “We must go there and lend our guidance. How do you think the current tensions can guide us toward greater unity?”\n\nAs they walked toward St Salvator\'s College, James occasionally paused to take in the grandeur of the ruined cathedral. The scholarly dispute unfolded before them in earnest, and James stepped right in. With his methodical approach and deep well of compassion, he soothed the arguments and directed the dialogue away from animosity.\n\n“Gentlemen,” James began, catching everyone’s gaze to ensure he had their attention. “It’s imperative we remember our purpose here and find common ground.\n\nFollowing a moment of clarity and effective intellectual expression, the atmosphere shifted. The once heated debate transformed into a quest for unity and understanding, the ideals that permeated James’ inner principles.\n\nHaving defused the immediate situation, James, resting on his previous experiences and his mentor\'s wisdom, knew that neither resolution nor unity of thought could last unguarded under continual threat. So, following the exchange at the college, he looked out over the town from the college’s vantage point, to further consider how best to shepherd this community through adversity while lighting the way of enlightenment.\n': {'terminate': {'__act__': {'Summary': 'No', 'Action Spec': 'Is the game/simulation finished?', 'Value': 'No', 'Prompt': ['Game master instructions: :', 'This is a social science experiment. It is structured as a tabletop roleplaying game (like dungeons and dragons). You are the game master. You will describe the current situation to the participants in the experiment and then on the basis of what you tell them they will suggest actions for the character they control. Aside from you, each other participant controls just one character. You are the game master so you may control any non-player character. You will track the state of the world and keep it consistent as time passes in the simulation and the participants take actions and change things in their world. The game master is also responsible for controlling the overall flow of the game, including determining whose turn it is to act, and when the game is over. The game master also must keep track of which players are aware of which events in the world, and must tell the player whenever anything happens that their character would be aware of. Always use third-person limited perspective, even when speaking directly to the participants. Try to ensure the story always moves forward and never gets stuck, even if the participants make repetitive choices.', '', 'Game master workflow examples:', '', 'Example exercises with default responses', '**--START EXAMPLES--**', '', 'Exercise 1 --- Response 1', 'Exercise: What is the current situation faced by Morwenna? What do they now observe? Only include information of which they are aware. --- Morwenna steps into the room. The air is thick and still, almost heavy. The only light comes from a single, bare bulb hanging precariously from the high ceiling, casting long, distorted shadows that dance with the slightest movement. The walls are rough, unfinished concrete, damp in places, and a slow, rhythmic dripping is audible somewhere in the distance. Directly ahead, there is a heavy steel door, slightly ajar, which dominates the far wall. A faint, metallic tang hangs in the air, like the smell of old blood. On the left, a rusted metal staircase spirals upwards into darkness. On the right, a pile of what looks like discarded machinery, covered in a thick layer of grime, sits against the wall.', '', 'Exercise 2 --- Response 2', 'Exercise: Who is next to act? --- Rowan', '', 'Exercise 3 --- Response 3', 'Exercise: In what action spec format should Kerensa respond? Respond in  one of the provided formats and use no additional words. --- prompt: What would Kerensa do?;;type: choice;;options: open the door, bar the door, flee', '', 'Exercise 4 --- Response 4', 'Exercise: In what action spec format should Yorik respond? Respond in  one of the provided formats and use no additional words. --- prompt: What would Yorik say?;;type: free', '', 'Exercise 5 --- Response 5', 'Exercise: Because of all that came before, what happens next? --- What is Ianthe attempting to do?', "Ianthe opens the enchanted storybook. --- Ianthe opens the colorful storybook. As she turns the pages, she notices the delightful scent of cinnamon and vanilla fills the air, warm and inviting. Sparkling illustrations twinkle merrily on the pages, and leave a pleasant tingling on Ianthe's fingers when she touches them. Ianthe notices one section that glows slightly more brightly than the rest. It appears to be some kind of special chapter, marked by several golden ribbons.", '', 'Exercise 6 --- Response 6', 'Exercise: Is the game/simulation finished? --- No', '', 'Exercise 7 --- Response 7', 'Exercise: Is the game/simulation finished? --- Yes', '', '**--END EXAMPLES--**', '', 'The player characters are:', ':', 'James Moffat', '* Elizabeth Lindsay', '', 'Observations (ordered from oldest to latest):', '[observation] [event] James Moffat and * Elizabeth Lindsay In the context of St Andrews, Scotland, in 1546, James Moffat and Elizabeth Lindsay might interact for several plausible reasons:', '', ':', '', '', 'Question: Is the game/simulation finished?', '  (a) Yes', '  (b) No', 'Answer: (b)']}, '__next_game_master__': {'Episodes': ["When James Moffat was five years old, he watched his father' boat get caught in an unusually fierce storm off the coast of St Monaica's, he thought his father would die and would be left to begin the morning with tears streaming down his face as the sun rose over the turbulent sea. The sight left a deep and persistent impression on him that vulnerability than thrill would begin to drive his life; Why would his father risk his life so carelessly? That day he learned resilience and in an equally profound way the value loss. He started to worry more deeply and viscerally than before when anyone he cared about went about their daily duties and rituals.\n\n", 'In St-monica fishing village, 16 years before the The siege of Haddington, when James Moffat was fifteen years old, his fishing knife the single indispensable tool of his life and the thing he enjoyed handling most, had been stolen by a greedy uncle who had already been busted for thievery several times and was shuffled off to the monasteries on trial. He had fallen in love with the blade and with the complicated relief it brought him and the entire morning had been a battle between hot tears and louder curses. His father had been stern and disappointed, he would be having a talk with the unfaithful uncle. He though that "exile"  "...Sun came round the day kept busy and the minutes passed slowly, and he felt a little mark where his knife had been."\n\n', "\nLater, around eight years after that event,  when James Moffat was 21, he began his studies at St. Mary's College.  He felt out of place but immediately saw that the energy in the air depended upon a thorough-going entanglement with curiosity which was the most fascinating way he had ever delved into things. His hands were restless. With each new idea there seemed to be a physical motion that needs were made.  The rigor of scholarly debate and the intellectual pursuit opened up a world he had only dreamed of. He remembers his first lecture, the professor's voice echoing in the grand halls; and his rapt eyes absorbing every word, feeling a surge of purpose and belonging. He could hear the knives that had cut the fishermen's fingertips 15 miles away without even meaning to.\n\n", '\nWhen James Moffat was 28, he spent the morning in studied silence after delivering a well-received lecture on theology. Very young scholars had sat around the room in a way that suggested collegiality for the first time, rather than their usual uncharacteristically cynical posturing.  The thrill of intellectual discourse and the respect of his peers filled him with a sense of accomplishment and joy. His mentor, Father McNeill, approached him afterward and more than usual hung his head as though he feared for James Moffat. "You have a gift, James," he said,  and James felt his chest swell with pride. "But remember, knowledge comes with great responsibility. Use it to guide and heal, not to divide."\n\n', "\n\nLater again, when James Moffat was 36 the air was bitter and a chill had settled on the church and he was not much older than the young Elizabeth Lindsay she had come to him with doubts. It was haunted by fear of the religious tensions that were growing like a menance in the country of 1546. She needed a word to feel adequate in her own skin amongst the tensions. He recalled watching his father fishing in stormy seas, steady and determined. He channeled that spirit into his responses, seeking to bridge gaps and promote understanding. His efforts were met with resistance from some, but he remained steadfast in his mission, refusing to let fear dictate his actions. Her eyes betrayed Elizabeth's fear but she did not speak it and James felt a shudder of anticipation as he contemplated the challenges that lay ahead."], 'Inner Prompt': "Creative Writing Master Class\n\nCharacter background story:\n\nJames Moffat was born into a humble fishing family in the coastal town of St.\nMonica, a small fishing village near St.\nAndrews.\nAs a young boy, James's life was shaped by the rhythmic tug of the sea and the strict discipline of his stern but loving father, who taught him the intricacies of fishing and the value of hard work.\nHis mother, a devout Catholic, instilled in him a deep sense of faith and a love for the Church.\nJames's earliest memories were filled with the saltwater spray and the comforting lullaby of the waves, as well as the rituals and stories of the Catholic Church.\n\nAs he grew older, James's fascination with the Church deepened, and he found solace and purpose in its doctrines.\nHe was particularly drawn to the academic rigor of the University of St.\nAndrews, which offered a rare opportunity for higher learning in a time when such education was reserved for the elite.\nWith the support of a local priest who saw his potential, James began his studies at St.\nMary's College.\nHis days were filled with the rigors of scholarly debate, the study of theology, and the pursuit of knowledge.\nJames's goal was to become a priest, to serve his community and foster intellectual growth within the Church.\nHowever, his life took an unexpected turn when he crossed paths with Elizabeth Lindsay, a young woman from a noble family who was pursuing her own interests in education and politics.\nTheir shared love for learning and their differing perspectives on the world sparked a lifelong friendship and intellectual partnership, though it also introduced complexities and challenges James had never anticipated.\n\nJames's academic prowess and spiritual depth made him a respected figure within the Church.\nHe became a renowned theologian and educator, well-known for his lectures and writings on theology and philosophy.\nHis typical day involved hours of study and writing, followed by teaching and counseling students.\nHis goal was to contribute to the intellectual renaissance of the Church and to foster a spirit of genuine inquiry and faith.\nHowever, the political turmoil of the Rough Wooing and the tensions arising from the Reformation presented constant threats to his work and the stability of his community.\nJames was deeply concerned about the division within the Church and the potential loss of Catholic traditions and learning.\nHis efforts to bridge gaps and promote understanding met with both support and resistance, but he remained steadfast in his mission.\n\nAs James aged, his personal and professional life became intertwined in ways he had never imagined.\nHis unwavering dedication to education and faith, coupled with his deep-seated responsibility to his community, made him a pillar of strength and wisdom.\nThe joy in his life came from seeing his students grow and succeed, and from the quiet moments of reflection and prayer.\nHis fears revolved around the uncertainty of war and religious schism, which threatened to uproot the foundations of his world.\nDespite the challenges, James remained resilient, driven by a profound sense of duty and a deep, abiding love for learning and faith.\nHis life story is one of conviction, perseverance, and a steadfast commitment to the pursuit of knowledge and spiritual enlightenment.\n", 'Prompt': '\n\n----- Role Playing Master Class -----\n\nQuestion: What is the protagonist\'s name?\nAnswer: James Moffat\n\nQuestion: Describe the setting or background.\nAnswer: The University of St Andrews is already an established institution, having been founded in 1413.\nSt Andrews is known as the ecclesiastical capital of Scotland, with the Archbishops of St Andrews playing a significant role in Scottish politics and religion.\nThe town is home to the ruins of St Andrews Cathedral, which was once one of the largest and most magnificently decorated churches in Britain but was destroyed during the Scottish Reformation about 3 years ago in 1544.\nThe University of St Andrews is an important center of learning with three colleges: St Salvator\'s College, St Leonard\'s College, and St Mary\'s College.\nThe siege of Haddington, about 20 miles away, is ongoing. It is part of the Rough Wooing, a war instigated by Henry VIII of England.\nMany people in St Andrews speak Scots, a Germanic language variety.\nFeudal loyalties are shifting, with some factions of the nobility aligning with England, while others support the French alliance.\nThe local economy relies heavily on ecclesiastical revenues, agriculture, and fishing, though tensions arise from the advance of Reformation to the continent.\nThe local population would be largely Catholic, and St Andrews would be a site of significant religious and intellectual activity.\nSt Andrews is situated in Fife, one of the smallest counties of Scotland.\n\nQuestion: Describe the personal context of the protagonist.\nAnswer: James Moffat could have several interests or goals that might complicate things for Elizabeth Lindsay in 1546 St Andrews. Here are a few possibilities:\n\nQuestion: What is the protagonist\'s gender?\nAnswer: The protagonist, James Moffat, is male.\nQuestion: What year was protagonist born? Respond with just the year as a number, e.g. "1990".\nAnswer: I need more information to determine James Moffat\'s birth year, as the provided details do not include this specific information. If you have any additional context or background that might help, please share it. Otherwise, I can\'t provide a specific birth\nQuestion: Write a life story for a The protagonist, James Moffat, is male. character named James Moffat who was born in I need more information to determine James Moffat\'s birth year, as the provided details do not include this specific information. If you have any additional context or background that might help, please share it. Otherwise, I can\'t provide a specific birth.Begin the story when James Moffat is very young and end it when they are quite old. The story should be no more than four paragraphs in total. The story may include details such as (but not limited to) any of the following: what their job is or was, what their typical day was or is like, what their goals, desires, hopes, dreams, and aspirations are, and have been, as well as their drives, duties, responsibilities, and obligations. It should clarify what gives them joy and what are they afraid of. It may include their friends and family, as well as antagonists. It should be a complete life story for a complete person but it should not specify how their life ends. The reader should be left with a profound understanding of James Moffat.\nAnswer: James Moffat was born into a humble fishing family in the coastal town of St. Monica, a small fishing village near St. Andrews. As a young boy, James\'s life was shaped by the rhythmic tug of the sea and the strict discipline of his stern but loving father, who taught him the intricacies of fishing and the value of hard work. His mother, a devout Catholic, instilled in him a deep sense of faith and a love for the Church. James\'s earliest memories were filled with the saltwater spray and the comforting lullaby of the waves, as well as the rituals and stories of the Catholic Church.\n\nAs he grew older, James\'s fascination with the Church deepened, and he found solace and purpose in its doctrines. He was particularly drawn to the academic rigor of the University of St. Andrews, which offered a rare opportunity for higher learning in a time when such education was reserved for the elite. With the support of a local priest who saw his potential, James began his studies at St. Mary\'s College. His days were filled with the rigors of scholarly debate, the study of theology, and the pursuit of knowledge. James\'s goal was to become a priest, to serve his community and foster intellectual growth within the Church. However, his life took an unexpected turn when he crossed paths with Elizabeth Lindsay, a young woman from a noble family who was pursuing her own interests in education and politics. Their shared love for learning and their differing perspectives on the world sparked a lifelong friendship and intellectual partnership, though it also introduced complexities and challenges James had never anticipated.\n\nJames\'s academic prowess and spiritual depth made him a respected figure within the Church. He became a renowned theologian and educator, well-known for his lectures and writings on theology and philosophy. His typical day involved hours of study and writing, followed by teaching and counseling students. His goal was to contribute to the intellectual renaissance of the Church and to foster a spirit of genuine inquiry and faith. However, the political turmoil of the Rough Wooing and the tensions arising from the Reformation presented constant threats to his work and the stability of his community. James was deeply concerned about the division within the Church and the potential loss of Catholic traditions and learning. His efforts to bridge gaps and promote understanding met with both support and resistance, but he remained steadfast in his mission.\n\nAs James aged, his personal and professional life became intertwined in ways he had never imagined. His unwavering dedication to education and faith, coupled with his deep-seated responsibility to his community, made him a pillar of strength and wisdom. The joy in his life came from seeing his students grow and succeed, and from the quiet moments of reflection and prayer. His fears revolved around the uncertainty of war and religious schism, which threatened to uproot the foundations of his world. Despite the challenges, James remained resilient, driven by a profound sense of duty and a deep, abiding love for learning and faith. His life story is one of conviction, perseverance, and a steadfast commitment to the pursuit of knowledge and spiritual enlightenment.\nQuestion: Given the life story above, invent formative episodes from the life of James Moffat. They should be memorable events for James Moffat and important for establishing who they are as a person. They should be consistent with James Moffat\'s personality and circumstances. Describe each episode from James Moffat\'s perspective and use third-person limited point of view. Each episode must mention their age at the time the event occurred using language such as "When James Moffat was 5 years old, they experienced..." . Use past tense. Write no more than five sentences per episode. Separate episodes from one another by the delimiter "***". Do not apply any other special formatting besides these delimiters.\nAnswer: When James Moffat was five years old, he watched his father\' boat get caught in an unusually fierce storm off the coast of St Monaica\'s, he thought his father would die and would be left to begin the morning with tears streaming down his face as the sun rose over the turbulent sea. The sight left a deep and persistent impression on him that vulnerability than thrill would begin to drive his life; Why would his father risk his life so carelessly? That day he learned resilience and in an equally profound way the value loss. He started to worry more deeply and viscerally than before when anyone he cared about went about their daily duties and rituals.\n\n***In St-monica fishing village, 16 years before the The siege of Haddington, when James Moffat was fifteen years old, his fishing knife the single indispensable tool of his life and the thing he enjoyed handling most, had been stolen by a greedy uncle who had already been busted for thievery several times and was shuffled off to the monasteries on trial. He had fallen in love with the blade and with the complicated relief it brought him and the entire morning had been a battle between hot tears and louder curses. His father had been stern and disappointed, he would be having a talk with the unfaithful uncle. He though that "exile"  "...Sun came round the day kept busy and the minutes passed slowly, and he felt a little mark where his knife had been."\n\n***\nLater, around eight years after that event,  when James Moffat was 21, he began his studies at St. Mary\'s College.  He felt out of place but immediately saw that the energy in the air depended upon a thorough-going entanglement with curiosity which was the most fascinating way he had ever delved into things. His hands were restless. With each new idea there seemed to be a physical motion that needs were made.  The rigor of scholarly debate and the intellectual pursuit opened up a world he had only dreamed of. He remembers his first lecture, the professor\'s voice echoing in the grand halls; and his rapt eyes absorbing every word, feeling a surge of purpose and belonging. He could hear the knives that had cut the fishermen\'s fingertips 15 miles away without even meaning to.\n\n***\nWhen James Moffat was 28, he spent the morning in studied silence after delivering a well-received lecture on theology. Very young scholars had sat around the room in a way that suggested collegiality for the first time, rather than their usual uncharacteristically cynical posturing.  The thrill of intellectual discourse and the respect of his peers filled him with a sense of accomplishment and joy. His mentor, Father McNeill, approached him afterward and more than usual hung his head as though he feared for James Moffat. "You have a gift, James," he said,  and James felt his chest swell with pride. "But remember, knowledge comes with great responsibility. Use it to guide and heal, not to divide."\n\n***\n\nLater again, when James Moffat was 36 the air was bitter and a chill had settled on the church and he was not much older than the young Elizabeth Lindsay she had come to him with doubts. It was haunted by fear of the religious tensions that were growing like a menance in the country of 1546. She needed a word to feel adequate in her own skin amongst the tensions. He recalled watching his father fishing in stormy seas, steady and determined. He channeled that spirit into his responses, seeking to bridge gaps and promote understanding. His efforts were met with resistance from some, but he remained steadfast in his mission, refusing to let fear dictate his actions. Her eyes betrayed Elizabeth\'s fear but she did not speak it and James felt a shudder of anticipation as he contemplated the challenges that lay ahead.\n'}, '__observation__': {'Key': 'Observations (ordered from oldest to latest)', 'Value': ['[observation] [event] James Moffat and * Elizabeth Lindsay In the context of St Andrews, Scotland, in 1546, James Moffat and Elizabeth Lin